'''Winter triathlon''' is a [[Multisport race|multisport]] event involving the continuous and sequential completion of [[snowshoeing]] or [[running]], [[mountain biking]] or [[speed skating]] and [[cross-country skiing (sport)|cross-country skiing]], all on snow. Course distances are set on the day of the event to achieve a winning time of around 80–90 minutes, after taking account of the snow conditions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.triathlon.org/multisports/winter_triathlon/ |title=Winter Triathlon |publisher=International Triathlon Union |accessdate=16 February 2011}}</ref>
Since 2013 the [[International Triathlon Union]] created a new version of the sport, which consist of 5 km of snowshoeing, 12km of ice skating and 8km of cross-country skiing. It is called winter triathlon S3, because the three sports start with an S (snowshoes, skate, ski). The first ITU event was held in Quebec, Canada in February 2015. However, the Canadian national winter triathlon championships have been running for over 30 years. The Winterlude Triathlon is the oldest established winter triathlon in Canada. {{Cn|date=June 2017}}
The sport was denied inclusion in the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]], [[Russia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/index.php?news=1164748259 |title=Ski Cross To Be Olympic Sport In 2010 |date=28 November 2006 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |publisher=GamesBids.com}}</ref>
